---
import DocsLayout from '../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro'
import SectionHero from '../../components/SectionHero.astro'
import DocsMeta from '../../components/DocsMeta.astro'
import Callout from '../../components/Callout.astro'
import Steps from '../../components/Steps.astro'
import { ThemedShot } from '../../components/ThemedShot'
import fs from 'node:fs'
import path from 'node:path'
import { withBase } from '../../lib/path'
const detectionSvg = fs.readFileSync(path.resolve(process.cwd(), 'public/diagrams/series-detection.svg'), 'utf-8')
---
<DocsLayout title="Series & arcs">
  <SectionHero section="features" />
  <h1>Series & arcs</h1>
  <p>
    Long-running series — manga, light novels, multi-volume sagas — are first-class in Tome.
    Volumes group automatically, optional arcs subdivide an enormous series into readable chunks,
    and a status badge tells you at a glance whether more is coming.
  </p>
  <DocsMeta />

  <h2>How series are detected</h2>
  <p>
    On scan and on upload, Tome inspects the filename for a series name and volume index. Books
    that match get a <code>series</code> + <code>series_index</code> set on their record; books
    that don't end up in the <strong>"No Series"</strong> virtual bucket.
  </p>

  <div class="docs-diagram" set:html={detectionSvg} />

  <p>Filename patterns Tome understands:</p>
  <table>
    <thead><tr><th>Pattern</th><th>Becomes</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td><code>Berserk v01 (1990).cbz</code></td><td>Series "Berserk", index 1</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>Berserk - Vol. 02.cbz</code></td><td>Series "Berserk", index 2</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>One Piece 105.cbz</code></td><td>Series "One Piece", index 105</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>Title - Author (Year).epub</code></td><td>Standalone (no series)</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <Callout variant="tip" title="Organise on disk by series, not by author">
    For manga and light novels, name your library folder after the <em>series</em>, not the
    author: <code>library/Berserk/Berserk v01.cbz</code>, not
    <code>library/Kentaro Miura/Berserk v01.cbz</code>. Tome handles both, but series-grouping
    is what most multi-volume books actually want.
  </Callout>

  <h2>The series page</h2>

  <div class="docs-shot">
    <ThemedShot client:load name="series-detail" alt="Berserk series page with arcs and progress" />
  </div>

  <p>
    Every series gets its own page at <code>/series/{`{name}`}</code>. It shows:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>A grid of all volumes, in order</li>
    <li>Reading progress per volume (unread / reading / read), aggregated into a series-wide progress bar</li>
    <li>A status badge — <strong>ongoing</strong>, <strong>finished</strong>, <strong>hiatus</strong>, or <strong>unknown</strong> — pulled from <code>SeriesMeta</code></li>
    <li>If arcs are defined, volumes group into arc sections with a per-arc description</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Arcs</h2>
  <p>
    Arcs are how you subdivide a long series. Berserk's 40+ volumes split naturally into
    <em>Black Swordsman</em>, <em>Golden Age</em>, <em>Conviction</em>, etc. — defining those as
    arcs lets readers see structure instead of an undifferentiated wall of 40 covers.
  </p>

  <div class="docs-shot-bare">
    <ThemedShot client:load name="series-arcs-modal" alt="Manage Series modal — Arcs tab" />
  </div>

  <h3>Creating arcs</h3>
  <Steps>
    <li>Open the series page as an admin.</li>
    <li>Click <strong>Manage arcs</strong> in the header.</li>
    <li>Add an arc: name, start volume, end volume, optional description.</li>
    <li>Arcs can be inclusive ranges (e.g. 1–3 means volumes 1, 2, and 3) and can use fractional indices for half-volumes.</li>
    <li>Volumes outside any arc still show up in a default "Other volumes" section.</li>
  </Steps>

  <Callout variant="info" title="Arcs are admin-only">
    Anyone can see arcs once they're defined, but creating and editing them requires admin
    access. They're metadata about the series itself, not a per-user thing.
  </Callout>

  <h2>Series status</h2>
  <p>
    A series can be marked <code>ongoing</code>, <code>finished</code>, <code>hiatus</code>, or
    <code>unknown</code>. The badge appears on the series page and on the dashboard's series
    grid. Admins set status manually, or let <a href={withBase("/docs/scribe")}>Scribe</a> populate it from
    LLM knowledge via <code>/scribe series &lt;name&gt;</code>.
  </p>

  <h2>The "No Series" bucket</h2>
  <p>
    Standalone fiction — most western novels — ends up here. It's a virtual sidebar entry, not a
    real series; the books inside it still have all the usual library/type assignments.
  </p>

  <Callout variant="warning" title="If your series shows wrong volumes">
    Re-scanning is non-destructive. If a series is grouping incorrectly, edit the
    <code>series</code> + <code>series_index</code> fields on the offending books directly
    (Edit metadata on the book detail page), or use Scribe to bulk-fix:
    <code>/scribe update &lt;query&gt;</code>.
  </Callout>
</DocsLayout>
